<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>CONSULTATION RESPONSE</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0.15pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WWC0026</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0.15pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">                                              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s submission sets out the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Union</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s views on the key issues identified by the Committee in the terms of reference for the Inquiry. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">submission looks at definitions of the terms </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘white’ and ‘working class’,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> considers the reasons for the underachievement of white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, outlines key things that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government should be doing to address the issue and highlights some of the critical factors underpinning successful wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rk in schools to improve educational outcomes for white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class children.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would be happy to give oral evidence to the Select Committee.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is the largest teach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ers’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> union representing teachers and school leaders in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is extremely concerned that the Select Committee is focusing on white working class underachievement and not looking at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">underachievement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">across all ethnic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of working class pupils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">White working class children are not the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lowest achieving group.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘White working class’ is not a homogeneous group and the definitions of ‘white’ and ‘working class’ can be interpreted in different ways.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Questions must be raised about the nature of white working class underachievement and extent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to which it is an issue. The Select Committee must look critically at data and evidence about white working class underachievement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Social class is the strongest predictor of educational achievement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thnic background</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> gender </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also strong </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">indicators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of educational outcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he relationship between social class and educational outcome is reflected within ethnic background and gender categories</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and through international evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Select Committee should examine international evidence about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inequi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ties in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">education outcomes but needs to ensure that the evidence is used appropriately.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">factors associated with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> white working class </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">achievement and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">underachievement are complex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and varied</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and need to be examined carefully</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evidence challenges the assum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ption that working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class families do not value education and are reluctant to engage in their child’s education.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Teachers report that their work to promote the achievement of all pupils is undermined by the high-stakes accountability system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Soci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">factors have an impact on white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class achievement and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policies to tackle the causes of poverty and disadvantage can ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve a significant impact on reducing educational inequalities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Central Government must take strategic responsibility for addressing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the underachievement of white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class pupils and this should be supported by legislation and form part of a cross</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">government approach to tackling poverty, social exclusion and inequalities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Lessons can be learned from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">previous strategies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> address child poverty, including increased investment in education, creating an infrastructure for high quality early childcare and education, and investment in housing and health.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Important lessons can be learned from the Every Child Matters strategy. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e challenges involved in ensuring effective communication and collaboration across services highlight the importance of a nationally co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ordinated, strategic approach.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The pupil premium policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">targets additional resources to children eligible for free schoo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l meals but additional funding is needed to ensure that other gr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oups of children who need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">receive this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">additional support.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is receiving an increasing number of reports that some schools are ‘selecting’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their intake so that inc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lusive schools are taking disproportionate numbers of pupils who need additional support. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s Cost of Education survey highlights the pressures that some parents are under to pay for their child to attend school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Equality Act 2010 provides an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">important legal framework to ensure that actions to meet the needs of white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class pupils are framed in a way that does not undermine support to meet the needs of other groups of pupils. The public sector equality duty is an essential component of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Equality Act and should help schools and other public authorities to set priorities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The removal of the socioeconomic duty from the Equality Act 2010 is regrettable a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this would help to ensure that public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authorities consider socioeconomic factors as p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">art of mainstream planning and decision making. The Select Committee should press for the reintroduction of such a duty.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The change in 2011 to the accountability arrangements in respect of schools’ compliance with the community cohesion duty was a regretta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ble and retrograde step which has not supported schools’ efforts to promote inclusion and social mobility for all pupils.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Black Country Challenges provide evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the benefits of a strategic and well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">resourced approach to rai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sing attainment and closing attainment gaps that promote collaboration and co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">operation between schools in an area. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The extent of white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">class pupils’ educational underachievement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and the factors responsible for their underachievement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is concerned that the Select Committee is looking at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">white working class underachievement and not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relative achievement and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">un</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">derachievement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">working class pupils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regardless of ethnic background</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evidence shows that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is a mixed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">picture of the association between socioeconomic background, ethnicity and educational achievement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">white working class pupils are more likely to succeed educationally than their working class peers from Black Caribbean backgrounds.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Also, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">whi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le white working class pupils have the lowest levels of attainment in some local authorities, in other local authority areas white working class pupils perform higher on average than their peers from African Caribbean, Pakistani and Bangladeshi backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t is important to recognise that the terms ‘white’ and ‘working class’ do not refer to a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> homogeneous group, but cover a very diverse </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">range</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of pupils. Further, the terms themselves are highly contested and subject to much debate. While this response </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">does not examine the different interpretations of these terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in detail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need to consider these differences and examine outcomes for different groups of white and working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class pupils.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">riefly, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some definitions link the term ‘working c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lass’ to socioeconomic status. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ligibility for free school meals (FSM) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is sometimes used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as a definition of low socioeconomic status</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eographical area </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may be used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as an indicator of deprivation rather than individual social class. Social class may also be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> defined by measures such as home ownership, social deprivation and overcrowding.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he term ‘working class’ may be used to refer to people in certain occupations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or to historical family roots</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Further, it may be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ejorative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">refer to people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are une</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mployed or in the worst paid and most vulnerable jobs.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These examples illustrate that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘working class’ may be used in very different ways. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In certain instances, low achievement may actually form part of the definition. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Similarly, it is important to recog</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nise that the term ‘white’ refers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to a diverse group of people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. For example, the National Census breaks the category ‘white’ down into White English/Scottish/Welsh, Northern Irish/British; White Irish; White Gypsy or Irish Traveller and Any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ther White </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Background.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The other white background may include people from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Poland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Eastern Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as well as those from other parts of the world. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">educational outcomes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs of these groups may vary enormously. For example, Gypsy and Irish Traveller ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e the lowest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">attaining group </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> GCSEs.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Also, children from mobile Gypsy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Traveller families will have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">particular needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> associated with travelling and continuity of education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">White </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pupils will also be diverse in other respects. For example, the g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roup includes pupils from different religious backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">whereas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pupils from the same religious background may hold very different views and beliefs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Some white pupils will have a disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and/or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SEN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">white pupils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will be refugees</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Some white pupi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ls will be lesbian, gay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, bi-sexual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rans.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> racial dimension </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to the use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the term ‘white</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hite working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class’ may be used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">divisively </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">argue that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are to blame </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> scarce resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lack of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">jobs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the context of educational achievement, there is a significant risk that focusing on white working class underachievement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">leads to the assumption that racial discrimination is no longer a problem in schools.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These points illustrate that the Select </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Committee needs to take account of the breadth of the term ‘white working class’ and ensure that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tackle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class underachievement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">address the divers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and racialised ways in which ‘white working class</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> might be used.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Commit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tee will need to ensure that actions to address white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class underachievement do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not undermine work to raise the achievement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and address the needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of other groups.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While acknowledging the complexity of definitions and interpretations of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">white work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing class</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it is useful to examine evidence about the nature and extent of white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class underachievement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evidence shows that in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, social class is the strongest predictor of educational achievement.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many statistical studies highlight the li</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nk between parental occupation, income and parental qualifications and education outcomes.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> For example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> figures from the Youth Cohort Study show that 81% of children from higher professional backgrounds achieved 5 or more A*-C GCSEs compared to 42% of pu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pils whose parents were in routine occupations and just 34% of parents who had never worked or were long term unemployed.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The most recent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tatistical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">irst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elease on GCSE and equivalent attainment shows that the percentage of pupils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in receipt of FSM </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hieving 5 or more A*-C GCSEs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> including English and maths</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> declined slightly in the five</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">year period from 2007/08 (27.8%) to 2011/12 (26.3%).</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This suggests that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the impact of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">socioeconomic inequalities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> increasing.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Studies of ethnic background, gender</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> class reveal that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">social class is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">greatest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> determinant of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a child’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">educational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">progress and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">attainment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. At the same time,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ethnic background</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> gender</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> appear to be associated strongly with pupil outcomes and intersect with social class in complex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the evidence on ethnicity and gender suggests that pupils’ educational outcomes are affected by the impact of racialisation and gender-typing within a pupil’s educational career.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">OECD evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inds that students from lower socioeconomic backgrounds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">perform less well in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PISA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> than students from more affluent backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The finding applies across all education systems participating in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PISA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the OECD identifies significant differences in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> levels of inequity. Specifically, those education systems that do best in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PISA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have lower levels of inequity than other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (i.e. the gap between the performance of the highest performing students and the lowest performing students is smaller than tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t for other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proportion of disadvantaged students in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who perform well in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PISA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is below the OECD average.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is important to recognise the limitations of using evidence from other education systems. Context may be very important </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nderstanding outcomes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, historically, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ome </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lower levels of inequity within their society than others. It will be important for the Select Committee to examine international evidence about inequities in education outcomes but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Committee must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensure that evidence is used appropriately.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recent Ofsted report, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Unseen Children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> suggests that inner and outer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">West Midlands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have been successful in raising attainment of pupils from lower socioeconomic backgrounds to above the national average. However, these successes do not appear to extend to other regions of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which raises questions about the role of local authoritie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s and other local services in securing the best education for all pupils.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reasons for white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">class underachievement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The reasons for white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class underachievement are complex and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in part,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> linked to how the term is defined. However, the evid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ence above also indicates that s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chool and non-school factors combine to lower attainment of children and young people from disadvantaged backgrounds.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It may be suggested t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hat pupils from working class backgrounds have low expectations, lack appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">role models</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do not receive appropriate support at home</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It may also be suggested that white working class</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> families do not value education and are reluctant to engage with the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> child’s school. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence challenges these assumptions and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> indicat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reasons for underachievement are much more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">complex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some studies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">focus on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocial and economic factors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to explain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class underachievement. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y highlight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">problems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arising from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> housing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the neighbourhood, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lack of study space </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and no access to the internet), social factors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e.g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> poverty, role models,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> peer pressure),</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">social exclusion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the role of the media in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">portraying people from white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class backgrounds.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ational policies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have a significant impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">education ou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vidence shows that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">participation in pre-school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> education </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has a significant impact on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">education outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of children from lower socioeconomic backgrounds.</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In relation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the OECD draws a link between the national po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licy of offering a free nursery place to every three and four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">year old </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and improved education outcomes.</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Counter-intuitively, some policies to raise standards may have a negative impact on education outcomes. Judgements about school performance are based</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on a very narrow range of success criteria (e.g. performance in National Curriculum tests and GCSEs). In the context of a high-stakes accountability system, this has the unintended consequence of driving school priorities and the priorities of those who s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">upport school improvement. Teachers report to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that their work to promote the achievement of all pupils is undermined by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">priorities inherent within the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">accountability system. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Government’s role in delivering improved educational outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> for white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">class pupils</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The evidence above indicates that there are many reasons why white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class pupils underachieve. It shows that issues related to class cannot be considered in isolation of matters related ethnic background, gender and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">other equality matters. This highlights the need for a strategic approach to addressing white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class underachievement. Policies to address educational underachievement must form part of a broader strategy to tackle the social and economic factors th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at contribute to educational underachievement. They must form also part of a coherent approach to address equality issues more generally.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Coalition Government must take strategic responsibility for addressing the underachievement of white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">clas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s pupils. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This includes providing a legislative and policy framework for addressing issues of poverty and inequality and ensuring that actions take place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">coherently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">across government. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">entral Government has a responsibility to tackle child poverty and social exclusion. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believes that the c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ritical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> features of an effective strategy include:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the establishment of an effective strategy and regulatory framework for policy development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and implementation;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sustained investment in anti-poverty programmes;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ordinated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment policy on poverty; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the promotion and implementation of effective local approaches</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Current Coalition Government policy fails t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o address the issue of poverty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and does not offer a meaningful anti-poverty strategy beyond the pupil premium.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Previous </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approaches</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">addressed these principles. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, the Child Poverty Act 2010 provided a legislative framework that was supported by policies and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d sustained </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">public investment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to enhance the ability of key public services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in order </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to contribute to poverty reduction. This included changes to benefits, investment in housing and health services and substantial investment in high</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">quality childcare and e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arly education, including the creation and extension of Sure Start Children’s Centres in areas experiencing high levels of socioeconomic disadvantage and exclusion. In relation to schools, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e strat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> included increased investment in the schools budget an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d targeted work to support the educational attainment and progress of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">children in schools serving areas with high levels of poverty and disadvantage. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his element of the Child Poverty Strategy was associated with a clear narrowing of the attainment g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aps at Key Stages 2 and 4 between pupils from low-income backgrounds and their peers</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believes that the whole package of measures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was necessary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to address the underachievement of white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class pupils.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very Child Matters </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(ECM) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sought to improve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and life outcomes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the most vulnerable children, including those living in poverty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. A central component of the ECM agenda </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">involved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improving inter-agency working and collaboration across children’s services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The implemen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tation of ECM highlighted the difficulties involved in developing effective collaboration and inter-agency working. For example, feedback from teachers and school leaders to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> showed that there were significant challenges in developing effective c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommunication channels and differences in organisational cultures and terminology needed to be overcome. Further, teachers involved in inter-agency working, for example </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">special educational needs co-ordinators (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SENCOs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, came under substantial pressure to tak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e on work associated with co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ordinating partnership working and this added to already unrealistic workloads.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believes that this highlights the importance of a nationally co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ordinated, strategic approach to ensuring effective collaboration and in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ter-agency working. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evaluation of the full extended services in schools programme that was part of the ECM agenda indicated that the holistic approach adopted by extended services in schools had a positive impact on the attainment of pupils.</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The pupil </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">premium </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may be cited </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Coalition G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment initiative targeted at meeting the needs of the poorest children, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">children from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class backgrounds. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> welcomes the expectation that schools should spend the pupil premium on tho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se pupils eligible for the pupil premium</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. However, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he pupil premium is not additional money but money taken from other parts of the education budget. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This means that there is less money in the system for other pupils, some of whom will not be eligible for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the pupil premium but will have substantial needs. Schools are not receiving additional funding to support these pupils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT considers this to be a fundamental flaw in the Coalition Government’s strategy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cuts to services and school budgets, combi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ned with the Coalition Government’s policy of moving to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a market</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">driven model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> exacerbates the problem identified above. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he academies and free schools programme discourages schools from working collaboratively and co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">operatively and encourage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s them to see neighbouring schools as rivals. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is receiving an increasing number</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of reports about schools employing underhand tactics to discourage ‘undesirable’ children from applying to the school. This includes reports that headteachers are te</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lling prospective parents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of children with SEN </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that the school will not be able to meet their child’s needs and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they would be better considering the inclusive school ‘down the road’. It also includes examples of schools requiring parents to pay for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">expensive uniforms, trips and other activities. As a consequence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> schools that are seen as ‘inclusive’ schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> admi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disproportionate numbers of pupils that require additional support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. However, they do not receive additional funding to address thes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e needs because many of the pupils will not be eligible for the pupil premium or attract the additional high</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs SEN funding. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believes that this policy is having a disproportionately adverse impact on working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class pupils. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Focusing on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">equali</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ty matters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the Equality Act 2010 provides a legal framework for ensuring that all of those who share a protected characteristic (including white people) are not unlawfully discriminated against. The Equality Act </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2010 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also places a duty on public authoriti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> including maintained schools and academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to be proactive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It requires them to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> eliminate unlawful discrimination, advance equality of opportunity and foster good relations between groups. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schools also have two specific duties: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to publish information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> about their service users, including any inequalities among them; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to prepare and publish specific and measurable objectives.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana-Bold; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The public sector duty, if implemented appropriately, provides an essential framework for ensuring that the needs of differe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt groups are identified and met. For example, it requires authorities to collect and use evidence to identify equality issues. It also requires them to set priorities and to monitor and evaluate the impact of policies and practice both on the groups being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> targeted and on other groups. The emphasis of the public sector equality duty is on action leading to positive outcomes. The duty should not be burdensome and bureaucratic. It should build genuine and meaningful consideration of equality matters into main</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stream planning and decision-making.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The draft Equality Act 2010 included a socioeconomic duty which required strategic public authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such as local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to have regard to the need to reduce inequalities that result from socioeconomic disadvantage. Regrettably, the socioeconomic duty was removed from the Equality Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believes that the duty provided the means for ensuring that the needs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some of the most vulnerable children and families in society are met in a coherent and strategic way. Serious consideration should be given to introducing legislation that requires public authorities, including schools and academies, to address socioeconom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ic disadvantage. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Union</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believes that such legislation is vital in ensuring that socioeconomic disadvantage is tackled in a coherent and strategic way. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Maintained schools have a d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uty to promote community cohesion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and academy funding agreements require</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> academies to promote community cohesion. The duty provides an important means for schools to undertake work to raise the achievement of different groups of pupils including, white working class pupils. The NASUWT is concerned that Ofsted no longer inspect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s schools’ work to promote community cohesion and believes that the Select Committee should examine how the duty is being used and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its impact in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rais</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the achievement of pupils.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">teps </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">that can be taken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">to improve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">educational outcomes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">of white workin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">class pupils</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assumes that many of the responses to the Inquiry will include examples of successful strategies to improve educational outcomes of white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">class pupils. There are also reports available that outline and evaluate effective strategies. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ishes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to emphasise the importance of a strategic, well-resourced approach.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The London Challenge and similar challenges in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Black </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Country</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> provide evidence of these benefits. Critically, these challenges adopted a strategic approach to support across an area. Support was targeted where necessary and tailored to meet the needs of different groups of learners. The programmes were well r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">esourced and schools were encouraged to work together to share knowledge and expertise. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Union</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believes that the problems cited by HMCI in so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">called seaside towns arise because schools do not have access to this strategic support and because local autho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rities are not funded to operate in this way.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NASUWT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> welcomes the holistic approach adopted by Achievement for All (AfA), the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Union</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is concerned that AfA is reluctant to share information about the precise nature of the programme with schools un</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">less they pay to be involved in the programme. It is unclear whether AfA offers genuine value for money and schools are not able to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evaluate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> how they might best spend their money to meet the needs of pupils, including developing in-house strategies. This i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">llustrate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the fundamental weakness of a market model of education.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Strand, Steve (2007), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Minority Ethnic Pupils in the Longitudinal Study of Young People in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> DCSF Research Report RR-002. Department for Children, Schools and Families, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Gillborn, David and Kirton, Alison (2000), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:i